snippet.textDisplay:
I would like to debate the point on accentuating proportions to make the car look "better" in 1/64 scale. The topic is first mentioned at around 7:49 in the video.

I've been shopping for cars for a long time, and I find 1/64 models from other brands that keep proportions exactly the same as the real car to be far superior than enlarged wheels, flattened roofs, smaller windows and overly wide bodies. My eyes are trained to the point where I can almost instantly tell whether a new Hot Wheels casting is disproportionate or not based on how it looks. Come on, how does overly large wheels even look good? Idk how you guys see it, but to me, a smaller version of something is literally just that. There's no need to change the proportions or what not for the car to look "better". To me, accurately proportioned 1/64 models from other brands look so much better to the eye and in pictures that I take in my photobooth.

Moreover, Matchbox doesn't make accurately scaled models as well. They too, like Mattel, love using oversized wheels. That Tesla model S Nolan uses as an example? It's out of proportion too, on both the Hot Wheels and Matchbox example. The front wheel arch, for example, is too high on the matchbox version. The top of the front wheel arch is just below the tip of the headlights on the real car, but on the Matchbox version the top of the wheel arch is way above the tip of the headlights, causing the front to look unusually bloated and large when it should be relatively low-slung.
snippet.textOriginal:
I would like to debate the point on accentuating proportions to make the car look "better" in 1/64 scale. The topic is first mentioned at around 7:49 in the video.

I've been shopping for cars for a long time, and I find 1/64 models from other brands that keep proportions exactly the same as the real car to be far superior than enlarged wheels, flattened roofs, smaller windows and overly wide bodies. My eyes are trained to the point where I can almost instantly tell whether a new Hot Wheels casting is disproportionate or not based on how it looks. Come on, how does overly large wheels even look good? Idk how you guys see it, but to me, a smaller version of something is literally just that. There's no need to change the proportions or what not for the car to look "better". To me, accurately proportioned 1/64 models from other brands look so much better to the eye and in pictures that I take in my photobooth.

Moreover, Matchbox doesn't make accurately scaled models as well. They too, like Mattel, love using oversized wheels. That Tesla model S Nolan uses as an example? It's out of proportion too, on both the Hot Wheels and Matchbox example. The front wheel arch, for example, is too high on the matchbox version. The top of the front wheel arch is just below the tip of the headlights on the real car, but on the Matchbox version the top of the wheel arch is way above the tip of the headlights, causing the front to look unusually bloated and large when it should be relatively low-slung.
